ce:section.ce:para:
To demonstrate the effectiveness of the Zn@LDH@GQDs anode, the full cell consists of a Zn@LDH@GQDs anode and an NH4V4O10 cathode is assembled [54]. The anode is NH4V4O10 due to its greater specific capacity than the manganese-based material, and the Zn(OTf)2 electrolyte replaces the ZnSO4 electrolyte due to its superior compatibility with the vanadium-based anode material. The morphological characterization and chemical phase analysis in Fig. S30 show the successful preparation of NH4V4O10 nanoplates. Morever, EDS mapping analysis reveals that the elements N, V, and O are equally distributed on the surface of NH4V4O10 nanoplates (Fig. S31). Then, the CV of the full cell is tested at a sweep rate of 0.5 mV S
                        −1 to assess the energy storage kinetics after the composite coating is applied to the Zn anode (Fig. 6a
                        ). The comparable redox peaks indicate that the electrochemically inert coating is stable and does not generate any side reactions during the cycle. In addition, the Zn@LDH@GQDs//NH4V4O10 full cell exhibits a greater current response, indicating improved electrochemical activity. The anodic and cathodic peaks of Zn@LDH@GQDs//NH4V4O10 migrate to higher potentials with essentially no polarization as the scan rate increases (Fig. S32). As a result, the Zn@LDH@GQDs//NH4V4O10 full cells have a higher capacity and better electrochemical reactivity. Furthermore, the Zn@LDH@GQDs//NH4V4O10 full cell exhibits a low polarization voltage, demonstrating its good reversibility and low transfer potential resistance.
